FaceCloak: Adversarial Pixel Poisoning for Biometric Privacy Preservation
A self-contained, locally-run tool that uses white-box adversarial optimization to mathematically neutralize facial recognition systems while preserving complete visual fidelity for human observers.

Project Overview
Facial recognition has become one of the most pervasive and least consented-to forms of surveillance in the digital age. Companies routinely scrape social media and public web content to harvest billions of face images, building biometric databases without any individual's knowledge or permission. This project builds a practical countermeasure rooted in adversarial machine learning theory.
The core idea is deceptively elegant: a facial recognition model processes an image by compressing it into a high-dimensional numerical vector called an embedding. Two photos of the same person produce embeddings that are very close together in that vector space, and that closeness is how a match is declared. FaceCloak attacks this specific mechanism. It makes mathematically precise, microscopic adjustments to pixel values, so small they are invisible to the human visual system, that cause the embedding of the altered image to fly to a completely different region of the vector space. To a human, the two images are identical. To every facial recognition model that processes them, they represent entirely different, unrecognizable individuals.
The technical approach is Projected Gradient Descent applied directly to the image tensor, not to any model weights. The model itself is completely frozen. You are running backpropagation only to learn how to modify the input. This is the defining characteristic of white-box adversarial attacks.
The project will be deployed as a Gradio application on a Hugging Face Space, entirely free, with no external APIs, no cloud dependencies, and no data leaving the user's browser session. The entire pipeline, face detection, embedding extraction, adversarial optimization, and verification, runs locally within the Space's CPU environment.

Technical Foundation You Must Understand Before Building
Before writing a single line of code, you need a firm mental model of four concepts. Reading about them first will make every implementation decision obvious rather than confusing.
Facial Embeddings. FaceNet and similar models are trained using triplet loss or ArcFace loss to produce a mapping from face image to a 512-dimensional vector. The geometry of this space is the entire product: faces of the same person cluster together, faces of different people are far apart. Cosine similarity and Euclidean distance are the two metrics used to decide if two embeddings represent the same person.
White-Box Adversarial Attacks. In a white-box scenario, you have full access to the model's architecture and weights. This means you can compute the gradient of any scalar loss value all the way back through the model to the input pixels. This is just standard backpropagation, but instead of using the gradient to update weights, you use it to update pixel values.
Projected Gradient Descent. PGD is an iterative attack. In each step, you take a gradient step in the direction that maximizes your adversarial loss, then you project the result back onto an allowed perturbation set. The allowed set is defined by your norm constraint, either L-infinity (no individual pixel can move more than epsilon) or L2 (the total energy of the noise is bounded). The projection step is what keeps the image visually unchanged. Without it, the optimization would simply destroy the image entirely.
The Dual Loss Function. Your loss function has two terms in tension with each other. The first term, the adversarial term, wants to maximize the distance between the embedding of the original image and the embedding of the cloaked image. The second term, the perceptual fidelity term, penalizes any deviation of the cloaked image from the original. The balance between these two terms, controlled by a weighting hyperparameter, determines how aggressive versus how invisible the perturbation is. In practice, a well-tuned PGD with a strict epsilon constraint makes the fidelity term almost redundant because the epsilon constraint itself handles invisibility, but keeping both makes the optimization more stable.

Phase 1: Environment and Infrastructure Setup
This phase is about establishing your project skeleton before touching any machine learning code.
Step 1: Create your Hugging Face account and Space. Go to huggingface.co and create a free account if you do not have one. Navigate to your profile and create a new Space. Select Gradio as the SDK. Select CPU basic as the hardware, which is free. Give the Space a name matching your project title.
Step 2: Understand the Space file structure. A Hugging Face Gradio Space requires at minimum an app.py file and a requirements.txt file. The app.py is your entire application. The requirements.txt lists every Python package that the Space's build server needs to install. Everything else, model weights, cached files, temporary images, lives either in the repository or gets downloaded at runtime.
Step 3: Set up your local development environment. You will develop locally and push to the Space via Git. Clone your Space repository to your local machine using the Hugging Face Git URL provided in the Space settings. Create a Python virtual environment inside that cloned folder. This environment will mirror what runs on the Space.
Step 4: Install your core dependencies locally. The packages you need are torch, torchvision, facenet-pytorch, Pillow, numpy, and gradio. Install these in your virtual environment. Do not pin versions yet, let pip resolve them. Once everything works, you will pin them for the requirements.txt to ensure reproducible builds on the Space.
Step 5: Verify your local torch installation. Open a Python shell and confirm you can import torch, that torch.cuda.is_available() returns False (you are on CPU, which is expected), and that basic tensor operations work. This sanity check takes thirty seconds and saves hours of confusion later.
Step 6: Populate requirements.txt carefully. After your local environment is working, run pip freeze and selectively copy only the packages your project actually uses into requirements.txt. Do not paste the entire freeze output because it includes system-specific packages that will break the Space build. The key entries are torch, torchvision, facenet-pytorch, Pillow, numpy, and gradio. Specify versions explicitly once you have confirmed a working combination.

Phase 2: Face Detection and Embedding Extraction Pipeline
This phase builds the foundation that every other component depends on.
Step 7: Understand MTCNN. facenet-pytorch ships with MTCNN, a Multi-task Cascaded Convolutional Network, which handles face detection and alignment. It takes a raw image and returns a cropped, aligned face tensor of a fixed size (typically 160x160 pixels). Alignment is critical because FaceNet's embeddings are sensitive to facial pose. MTCNN handles this by finding facial landmarks and performing an affine transformation to normalize the face orientation before cropping.
Step 8: Understand InceptionResnetV1. This is the actual FaceNet model in facenet-pytorch. You will load it with pretrained='vggface2', which means it was trained on the VGGFace2 dataset. This pretrained version produces the 512-dimensional embeddings you will use. The model has roughly 23 million parameters but runs a single forward pass in milliseconds on CPU because inference on a 160x160 image is computationally trivial.
Step 9: Build the face detection function. Write a function that takes a PIL Image as input and returns the aligned face tensor. The MTCNN instance should be initialized with keep_all=False (you want only the primary face), image_size=160, and margin=20 (the margin adds context pixels around the detected face). The function should handle the failure case: if MTCNN returns None because no face was detected, your function should raise a clear, user-readable exception. This error will surface in the Gradio UI as a helpful message rather than a crash.
Step 10: Build the embedding extraction function. Write a function that takes the aligned face tensor and returns the 512-dimensional embedding vector as a numpy array. The InceptionResnetV1 model should be set to eval mode before inference. You will pass the face tensor through the model in a torch.no_grad() context for efficiency during the non-adversarial passes. The model returns a tensor; convert it to a numpy array for storage and cosine similarity calculations.
Step 11: Build the similarity scoring function. Write a function that takes two embedding vectors and returns a cosine similarity score between -1 and 1, where 1 means identical and values near 0 or negative mean unrelated faces. Cosine similarity is preferable to Euclidean distance for this demo because it is normalized and immediately interpretable as a percentage-like score. Scipy has a cosine distance function, but you can also implement it directly with numpy as the dot product of the two unit-normalized vectors.
Step 12: Test this pipeline end to end. Download any two photos of the same person and any photo of a different person. Run your pipeline on all three. Confirm that same-person pairs produce similarity scores above 0.8 and different-person pairs produce scores below 0.3. If your numbers do not match these rough benchmarks, your pipeline has a bug, typically in tensor normalization or in the keep_all parameter of MTCNN.

Phase 3: The Adversarial Cloaking Engine
This is the intellectual core of the project. Take your time with each step.
Step 13: Restructure your embedding pipeline for gradient flow. The embedding extraction you built in Phase 2 used torch.no_grad() for efficiency. The adversarial loop needs gradients to flow through the model, so you need a second version of the embedding function that does not use no_grad(). The model weights are still frozen, meaning you will call model.eval() and you will not call optimizer.zero_grad() on any model parameter. But the computation graph must be alive so that when you call loss.backward(), the gradient reaches the image tensor.
Step 14: Understand the perturbation tensor. In PGD, you do not directly optimize the image pixel values. Instead, you maintain a separate perturbation tensor, often called delta, initialized to all zeros and having the same shape as the face tensor. The cloaked image at any point in the optimization is simply the original face tensor plus delta. This separation matters because you need to clip delta independently to enforce the epsilon constraint. The cloaked tensor is always reconstructed as original plus delta, and it is the cloaked tensor that gets fed to the model.
Step 15: Set up the PGD initialization. Before the loop begins, you need four things: the original face tensor stored as a constant that never changes (detach it from any graph and call requires_grad=False), the original embedding computed once and stored as a constant, the perturbation tensor delta initialized to zeros with requires_grad=True, and your hyperparameters: epsilon (the maximum perturbation magnitude per pixel, typically 0.02 to 0.05 on a 0-to-1 normalized scale), alpha (the step size per iteration, typically epsilon divided by 10), and num_steps (the number of PGD iterations, typically 50 to 200 for CPU).
Step 16: Implement the PGD loop body. Each iteration of the loop has exactly four operations. First, construct the cloaked tensor by adding delta to the original tensor and clamping the result to the valid pixel range (0 to 1 if normalized, or whatever range your model expects). Second, pass the cloaked tensor through the frozen model to get the cloaked embedding. Third, compute the loss. Fourth, call loss.backward(), read delta.grad, take a gradient step, project delta back onto the epsilon ball, and reset the gradient.
Step 17: Implement the loss function carefully. Your primary adversarial loss is negative cosine similarity between the original embedding and the cloaked embedding. You want to maximize the distance between these two embeddings, which means minimizing negative cosine similarity. PyTorch's torch.nn.functional has a cosine_similarity function that operates on tensors. You take the original embedding tensor (detached, as a constant) and the cloaked embedding tensor (active in the computation graph), compute cosine similarity, and negate it to get a value you want to minimize. Optionally, add a small L2 penalty term on delta itself, weighted by a small lambda value like 0.01, to add gentle regularization.
Step 18: Implement the gradient step and projection. After loss.backward(), delta.grad contains the gradient of the loss with respect to each pixel perturbation. Take the gradient sign (torch.sign(delta.grad)) for L-infinity PGD, multiply by alpha, and add to delta. Then project: clamp delta to the range (-epsilon, +epsilon). This is the L-infinity projection. It enforces that no single pixel deviates from the original by more than epsilon. After updating delta, critically, you must zero out delta.grad before the next iteration. Call delta.grad.zero_() or detach and re-enable gradients. If you forget this, gradients will accumulate across iterations and your loop will produce garbage.
Step 19: Handle tensor normalization carefully. FaceNet models expect input normalized to a specific range, typically mean-subtracted and standard-deviation-normalized using ImageNet statistics. MTCNN handles part of this. Make sure you understand exactly what numerical range the tensor is in when it enters InceptionResnetV1, because your epsilon value must be specified in the same units. If the tensor values range from roughly -1 to 1 after normalization, an epsilon of 0.05 is very tight. If they range from 0 to 255, an epsilon of 8 (as used in many adversarial ML papers) is the appropriate scale. Getting this wrong is the single most common source of invisible perturbations that have no effect on the model.
Step 20: Return the cloaked image as a PIL Image. After the loop, construct the final cloaked tensor (original plus final delta, clamped), reverse the normalization transform, convert back to a 0-255 uint8 numpy array, and convert to a PIL Image. This is the downloadable output.

Phase 4: The Verification and Scoring System
Step 21: Build the post-cloak verification pipeline. After cloaking, your app must automatically run verification without any user interaction. Take the cloaked PIL Image, run it through MTCNN again to get a fresh aligned face tensor (do not reuse the original's aligned tensor because you want to simulate exactly what would happen if someone uploaded the cloaked image independently), extract its embedding using the frozen model, and compute cosine similarity with the original embedding.
Step 22: Design the score interpretation. You want to display the score in a human-friendly way. A raw cosine similarity number means nothing to a non-technical user. Display it as a percentage match. A score above 0.7 means "Face Matched: this is recognized as the same person." A score below 0.3 means "Identity Cloaked: this face is unrecognizable to the AI." A score in between means "Partial Cloak: try increasing iterations or epsilon." This gives the reviewer immediate, unambiguous feedback about whether the attack succeeded.
Step 23: Implement a before-and-after visual diff for technical reviewers. Compute the absolute difference between the original face tensor and the cloaked face tensor, scale it up by a large factor (50x to 100x), and display this amplified difference as a separate image. To the naked eye, this should look like uniform gray noise with no discernible facial features, proving the perturbation is spatially unstructured. If the diff image shows obvious facial contours or bright spots on specific facial landmarks, your epsilon is too large and the perturbation is becoming visible.

Phase 5: Gradio Interface Design
Step 24: Plan your interface layout before building it. The UI has three logical sections: the input section, the processing section, and the results section. Think through the user journey. The reviewer should be able to complete the entire demo in under two minutes with zero prior knowledge of adversarial ML.
Step 25: Build the input section. A single Gradio Image component for uploading the selfie. Below it, three sliders for the technical hyperparameters: epsilon (range 0.01 to 0.10, default 0.03), number of PGD steps (range 20 to 300, default 100), and step size alpha as a fraction of epsilon (range 0.05 to 0.5, default 0.1). Add a small info accordion below the sliders that explains in plain English what each parameter does. Default values should produce a successful cloak on most images without adjustment.
Step 26: Build the processing trigger. A single button labeled "Generate Cloak." All computation triggers from this one button click. During computation, Gradio's built-in loading state will show a spinner. You do not need to implement this manually.
Step 27: Build the results section. Use Gradio's Row component to create a side-by-side layout. Left column: the original cropped and aligned face at 160x160 pixels, enlarged for display, with the label "Original Image" and the original match score showing "Match Score: 99.X%." Right column: the cloaked image at the same display size with the label "Cloaked Image" and the post-cloak score showing "Match Score: X.X%." Below the two images, display the amplified noise visualization with the label "Adversarial Noise (50x amplified for visibility)." Below that, a single prominent download button for the full-resolution cloaked image.
Step 28: Add a live status text area. During computation, update a Gradio Textbox component with progress information: "Step 1 of 100: Current match score 94.2%", "Step 50 of 100: Current match score 43.1%", etc. This makes the optimization process visible and turns what would be a black-box wait into an engaging real-time demonstration. To implement this in Gradio, you will use a generator function that yields intermediate state updates rather than a standard function that returns once.
Step 29: Write the interface copy carefully. Every label, tooltip, and description in the UI should be understandable to someone with no ML background. Avoid jargon in the user-facing text. Reserve technical language for the accordion info boxes. The headline above the app should read something like "Upload your photo. Watch AI become blind to your face." The explanation below should be one sentence: "This tool uses adversarial mathematics to make microscopic pixel changes that are invisible to humans but completely scramble AI facial recognition systems."

Phase 6: Robustness, Edge Cases, and Hardening
Step 30: Handle the no-face-detected case gracefully. If MTCNN returns None, display a friendly error: "No face detected in this image. Please upload a clear, well-lit photo where your face is visible and forward-facing." Do not let the app crash silently.
Step 31: Handle multiple faces. If MTCNN detects multiple faces, keep_all=False will choose the largest face by default. Add a note to the UI: "If multiple faces are present, the largest face in the image will be cloaked."
Step 32: Handle extremely low-quality or small images. If the uploaded image is smaller than 80x80 pixels after MTCNN cropping, the face is too low resolution for reliable embedding extraction. Add a check and display a message asking for a higher resolution photo.
Step 33: Handle the case where the attack partially fails. Some faces, due to unusual lighting or poses, are harder to cloak within a strict epsilon. If after all iterations the match score is still above 0.5, display a warning: "Partial cloak achieved. Try increasing the number of steps or the epsilon value." This is honest feedback and guides the user rather than presenting a misleading result.
Step 34: Add input image size limits. Large images slow down MTCNN preprocessing. Automatically resize any uploaded image so its longer dimension is no more than 1024 pixels before passing to MTCNN. This has no effect on quality since MTCNN crops to 160x160 anyway.
Step 35: Test with diverse inputs. Test your pipeline with images that have different skin tones, glasses, facial hair, different lighting conditions, and different facial orientations. Note which conditions produce weaker cloaks and document this in the app's description, because transparency about limitations is a mark of rigorous work.
